answers.body_markdown:
This function will give you the result you want. It sorts the array using `arsort` (to retain the keys), then finds the third (possibly equal) highest value, and returns all values in the array that are greater than or equal to that:

    function top_3($array) {
        // reverse sort the array, retaining keys
        arsort($array);
        // get the third highest value
        $min = array_values($array)[2];
        return array_filter($array, function ($v) use ($min) { return $v &gt;= $min; });
    }
    print_r(top_3($array1));
    print_r(top_3($array2));
    print_r(top_3($array3));

Output:

    Array
    (
        [A] =&gt; 7
        [B] =&gt; 5
        [C] =&gt; 5
    )
    Array
    (
        [A] =&gt; 7
        [B] =&gt; 7
        [C] =&gt; 5
        [D] =&gt; 5
        [E] =&gt; 5
    )
    Array
    (
        [A] =&gt; 7
        [B] =&gt; 7
        [C] =&gt; 7
        [D] =&gt; 7
    )

[Demo on 3v4l.org][1]


  [1]: https://3v4l.org/vCCkG

I like Nick&#39;s solution. That said, here&#39;s my old school procedural approach.

    function array_top($array,$target=3) {
    	arsort($array);
    	
    	$result=[];
    	$previous=NULL;
    	foreach ($array as $index=&gt;$value) {
    		if ((count($result)&gt;=$target) and ($value!=$previous)) break;
    		$result[$index]=$value;
    		$previous=$value;
    	}
    
    	return $result;
    }
    
    $array1=[&#39;A&#39;=&gt;7,&#39;B&#39;=&gt;5,&#39;C&#39;=&gt;5,&#39;D&#39;=&gt;4,&#39;E&#39;=&gt;3,&#39;F&#39;=&gt;3,&#39;G&#39;=&gt;2];
